This year, women received Nobel Prizes in all categories except Physics.
Five women, which is a record number, received today in Stockholm from the hands of King Charles XVI Gustav of Sweden the Nobel Prizes this year, in specialized categories and in literature.
In addition to the four scientists, a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller, was among the winners.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as fellow American scientist Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Ada Jonath, Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for explaining the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last prize, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was awarded to American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for analyzing an economic report.
The only specialized category, without an award-winning woman, was Physics.
The award was given today by scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each awardee collected the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of the money received.
