The secret of splendor over Norway solved: Russians tested a missile
A special light effect of unknown origin was observed over Norway.
Russia’s defence ministry said it had tested an intercontinental ballistic missile near its border with Norway.
The "Bulava"-type missile, previously destined to be the pride of the Russian army, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Not even its repeated presence in missile tests has had the desired effect on the success of test flights.
Bulavá, in most cases, did not fly or there was an air failure.
In the Russian newspapers they write of "Bulava" as of "a missile that does not fly".
A missile that does not fly, but shines.
During this, the 13th test, no problems occurred at first.
At the end of the flight there were again technical problems in the aircraft.
Probably the engine exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulava" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which floated submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile makes it possible to launch from a vessel that is moving and submerged at the same time.
That’s why it’s likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed “Bulava.”
The Norwegians did not hesitate from the first moment that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by stating that one cannot simply speak of a failure.
The first two stages of the missile held up and the breakdown occurred in the third.
In the above cases the engines broke down immediately in the first stage.
Although none of the launches went completely error-free, according to the Ministry of Defense management only six of the thirteen failed.
