Pneumococcal Vaccine Will Be Free and Voluntary
The pneumococcal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As a first vaccine it must be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, there are already opinions that the compulsory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine culminate.
The Institute of Medicines is already setting the maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
Experts have already made this clear in the vaccination procedure.
The New Vaccine
Free vaccines for children born in August
From January, children born since August 2 of last year will be able to receive the pneumococcal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is that you have not received a single dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or earlier, have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine has to be received between the third and fifth month of age of child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily allowed their children to be vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents, however, paid for a dose of 1600 kroner and more.
To vaccinate younger children, four doses are needed.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend 300 to 450,000 crowns annually on vaccines.
However, they will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far the state spent for all the vaccination of children approximately 500,000 annually.
The covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and septicemia.
Pneumococcal infections in our country die every year according to research in hospitals 28 children no older than 10 years of age.
In addition to the Czech Republic pneumococcal vaccine coverage in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However, at the same time there are opinions, that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
From January it must be covered by the insurance companies and voluntary.
The mandatory vaccination would be better, said Rudolf Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD>, the head of the Nahlas civic association.
Their association has been spreading pneumococcal vaccines for a long time.
Experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfiedwith the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It is not completely ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path we have to take now, Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD> mentioned.
The Ministry of Health, however, does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
At this moment we do not think about it at all, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>.
Voluntary Vaccine Has Its Disadvantages, Doctors Say
The president of the society of pediatricians Odborná spole<0xC4><0x8D>nost praktick<0xC3><0xBD>ch d<0xC4><0x9B>tsk<0xC3><0xBD>ch léka<0xC5><0x99><0xC5><0xAF> Hana Cabrnochová recognizes that the voluntary vaccine has its disadvantages.
"In the situation, when the vaccine costs such a high amount, we relatively understand the political decision to have started vaccination as a volunteer," says Cabrnochová.
Experts expect that from next year more than 80 percent of young parents will allow their babies to be vaccinated against pneumococci.
The pneumococcal vaccine is a big change also because as the first vaccination in children is covered by health companies, not the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, then save on treatment, explains Cabrnochová.
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, pediatricians are concerned about buying vaccines.
Previously, vaccines had to be purchased by insurance companies and distributed to doctors, just as when the state gives them other vaccines.
Some MPs, however, were afraid that insurance companies could “take the money out of health insurance.”
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines and wait until they are paid for by insurance companies.
It is estimated, that pediatricians will invest in vaccinations 40,000 per month, which is a remarkable sum.
It won't be easy, says Cabrnochová.
