Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what U.N. climate chief Yvo de Boer described as "the big picture."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred talks on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
