Management Revolution or the End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more so, business intelligence.
Indeed, Business Intelligence “demands that all parties involved ... have a proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision”; it needs from employees a commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would consist in putting employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange’s employee questionnaire, incite management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory that the American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a posture of mechanistic management, unsuitable for today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies means adopting a finalistic view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilization factors, company managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “on the spot”.
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: for 'just war' Obama receives praise from the right
On Friday, the American right, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of a "just war" against America's enemies, hailed the speech Obama had delivered on Thursday.
The conservatives, who had discredited Obama’s Oct. 9 award, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, said Ms. Palin, a leading figure in the right wing of the Republican party, to USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the issue of “sometimes necessary” war in her recently published memoirs.
