The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters tall that ran on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in Thursday's Science journal.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we’ve found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day—this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Natural History Museum.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered the remains of five specimens in total.
Finding Confirms Theories About Ancient History of Dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithisaurus belongs to the herbivorous trinvors (for example).
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, in Tawa’s skull, researchers found signs of air pockets, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa's case, the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed airbags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves migrating to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurians first emerged there.
Accordingly, the three genealogical lineages were separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa the remains of two other not closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in modern-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
Success stories weren’t eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
