Dream worlds
In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only in the case of the mentally ill and the drug addicts that the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unhindered indulge in the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, whoever experiences sleep-like states during waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is considered most often in the modern Western world to be mad or drug addict, or at least maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or the drugged.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to blur.
Dream-modified states of alertness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and the psychoses and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disrupted.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and insane thoughts often occur.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of sleep in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the nonsense, formations of madness, and hopes".
It is the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
Its body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over him, he is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red grimaces like blood, deformed, grinding their teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Screaming, evil voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls out two wires from the stereo, ties them up to form a hanging knot, and fastens them on a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs into a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump.
The rope is loosened.
Let it serve you as a lesson!, shout the voices in a chorus that bursts his eardrums, "go to the clinic and have yourself healed!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, taking medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the most profound despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most frequent disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, disorders in the relationship, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the gates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the general psychiatric clinic of the Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning addressed to him.
At the same time he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations rely on reality, the distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers it is still unknown why our brains make cabriolas.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can cause anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not everyone develops a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a previous disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis because they interfere with the brain’s transmitting system.
When the brain heats up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive medications to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The Unreal World in Our Head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychoses, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s and cranioencephalic trauma .
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer from hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or under-inhibited; when our brain heats up, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, the evil of loves or other brain states of exception.
