In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it weren't for those pictures and the voices.
Sometimes, during recess, it happens that a clumsy boy with long, dark hair speaks to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her with surprise; no one but her hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a bit of a strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she’s not dreaming.
She’s awake and she sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next door.
You can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the guy.
Sometimes she wonders if she's crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class he can sometimes not follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is presenting a new partner, while for the rest he explains in a visible and audible way the mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for the sleep to arrive, which is often late and scarce, he does not know whether he is awake or dreaming, whether the images he sees, the grimaces or the girl with bleeding cuts in his arms and legs, appear before his eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
Her parents and friends haven't told her anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She approved last year selectivity and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations have been gone for a year.
Since she’s come in contact over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, she knows she’s not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while he will start to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unemployed and is in charge of looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was as a child afraid of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he has been calling daddy since he had the use of reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," Kasten says, "takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nighttime fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that her patients appreciate her hallucinations as a special skill.
Borderline situation between sleep and hallucination
In this world too consciously focused, imaginary experiences are usually pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatric and psychotherapy clinic of the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
The dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that later can not differentiate from being awake.
Dream conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of self or of the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with a proper and imaginary world that is decoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a change of world occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own capacity of creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich also describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old when his conscience embarked on several-day journeys following heart valve surgery with heart transplantation included, while his body was doomed to immobility in the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he found himself prostrate in bed, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle abducted him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the Alps with snow firn and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so it describes your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental travel are, many years later, much clearer, even in the irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations, and narcotics show how fragile the inner reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Every modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
