75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and career path of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, start cohabitation as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time of their vital trajectory to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on motherhood, although less on the timing of pairing", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when marrying and having the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which they marry and have their first child.
The difference also remains between women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years old, those who had elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is also another division between women based on their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and prioritize obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child.
