Emergency braking aid is now compulsory
As with ABS anti-lock brakes and will pass ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all passenger cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of absence is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian protection although, by its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by range.
The emergency braking assistant increases the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver’s foot.
But it doesn’t always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not hit the brakes before the collision and half of them did not take full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided a year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four losses with damage to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
