In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading firm; 80% of the valuations are made with its products.
The other firms that compete in the field of appraisal tools and elaboration of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with data supplied by manufacturers is far from straightforward.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, in Spain they work with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with the information in different formats.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, to the point that more versions, variants and engines have been launched in the last five years than in the previous fifteen.
As soon as a new car hits the market, these companies get to work.
It is a very arduous task, because you have to catalog each of the thousands of parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, a "smart" graphic image is made of each model where different tourist parts can be "pinched".
If it is a wind mass model, the job can be ready in a week if the process goes very fast.
If it is a minority car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models have information about Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini, for example.
As for the mobile fleet that circulates, they exceed 99%.
To carry out the documentation work and the elaboration of the databases, Audatex has eight centers spread around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them is specialized in specific brands.
The national headquarters is in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros per year in the development of these databases.
2.5 million data are included each month, and customers receive updates every other day.
The elaboration of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer varied products.
The most frequent use focuses on repair and maintenance, but depending on which countries there are also tools for managing scrap parts or for calculating the venal or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used ones in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does in the United States.
In view of the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support they can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, the star product being AudaPlus, the standard solution for claims assessment, intended for experts.
Includes cars, motorcycles, and light or heavy commercial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the estimated repair times by the manufacturer or the paint bars.
This tool is paid according to use, for each rating.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, a maximum of ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which carries out thousands of expert reviews, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line only with its frame number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle moons, and AudaSubastas is a service open to the professional sector on the internet that allows you to bid for vehicles declared total loss.
Its statistics service is very useful to identify trends, perform geodemographic analysis or know the deviations by brands or models.
One can study, for example, how many models of a certain brand have gone through the workshop due to breakdowns or how many have suffered serious losses in a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It markets, among others, GT Estimate, which is also aimed at experts and also provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damages, breakdowns or maintenance of the automobile.
The Gt Appraisal Guide is your historical reference product in the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
